\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
The hole theory of supeconductivity was first presented by Hirch and Marsiglio in 1989\cite{hirschfirsthole} as an attempt to explain the mechanism for superconductivity in the, then recently discovered, high temperature superconductors.  In the ensuing twenty-five years, that seminal first article has been cited 191 times and, Hirsch has continued to develop the theory and now posits it as a viable explanation for superconductivity in all superconducting materials.  The proposed research is a series of experimental tests of the theory.  Each of the tests however, will also produce data for previously uncharacterized parameters and dynamic behaviors of bulk superconductors. 
\end{abstract}

\maketitle % title page is now complet


\section{Introduction}
To date, there are no reliable methods for predicting where to look for new superconducting materials.  Chapnik met with empirical success in the 1960s and 70s exploring materials with positive Hall coefficients indicating that the intrinsic normal state charge carriers were in fact holes instead of electrons.  After the surprising announcement of high temperature superconducting materials in the 1980s, it was found that conventional BCS theory could not produce successful models for them.  Jorge Hirsch and F. Magliaso proposed a hole pairing model with an associated Hamiltonian based on nearest neighbor hopping potentials.  In addition to providing a plausible model of the superconducting behavior of these new materials, their model also offered a more basic understanding of several superconducting phenomena.  If experimentally verified, this hole pairing model could serve as a jumping off point to guide deterministic searches new superconducting compounds.  It provides a simple, yet rigorous and clear mechanism for many superconducting dynamic behaviors such as the Meissner effect and <add more dynamic predictions>.
