\section{Theoretical Background}
The theory of hole sueprconductivity will be developed using the following set of assumptions and logcial scaffolding.  
\\
\\
Assumption: the charged particles forming the paired super-current carriers are in fact holes located near the Fermi level of the sample material, not electrons foudn lower in the band.
\\
\\
As the supercondcutor cools, holes pair, lowering their kinetic energy, consequntly expanding their wavelengths to several 1000 times the size of the unpaired atomic radii.  A convenient model for this behavior can be found in the covalent bond of $H_2$.  A quantitative expression for this expanded radius can be logically deduced\cite{hirschlondondepth}.  Starting with the experimentally verified property of perfect diamagnetism, we can show that the supercarriers must expand to a radius eqivalent to the London penetrtion depth for the material. 
\\
\\

4.  These radii are so large that it is energetically favorable for the paired holes have to align their phases creating coherency on a macroscopic level across the entire superconducting sample.
