\section{Proposed Research}
\textbf{List of experiments}
The proposed research will focus on two specific predictions made by the hole theory of superconductivity.  The first prediction is that due to the giant-atom nature of superconducting materials, Bremsstrahlung radiation should be emitted when a superconductor is quenched.  The second is that atoms in the material have a much larger outer orbital due to the kinetic energy lowering of the paired carrier wave functions and that this expanded orbital will change the mean potential of the atom.  The theory predicts changes of a large enough magnitude that they should be detectable by simple electron diffraction techniques.
\\
The x-ray energy predicted by the theory scales linearly with sample radius and is derived by Hirsch\cite{hirschradiation}, (see equation 46), as,
\\
$E = \hbar \omega_m = \dfrac{R}{R_c}m_c c^2$
\\
(insert equation here), while the flux of the radiation scales with the surface area of the sample.  For a spherical sample, the flux scales as the square of the radius of the sample, (insert flux equation here).



